="ArticleLeadArt_figure__1APAw"><div class="ArticleLeadArt_media__2ABbG"><img src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/1A3BhvuYjLSH3rSOAg6sOZzo3Nk=/0x0:2500x1406/720x405/https://cdn.theatlantic.com/assets/media/img/mt/2020/10/Montague_10_21_20_final/original.jpg" srcSet="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/1A3BhvuYjLSH3rSOAg6sOZzo3Nk=/0x0:2500x1406/720x405/https://cdn.theatlantic.com/assets/media/img/mt/2020/10/Montague_10_21_20_final/original.jpg, https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/5-Rmr2S2ZsgoQ4ziOmgOAEjX_QQ=/0x0:2500x1406/1440x810/https://cdn.theatlantic.com/assets/media/img/mt/2020/10/Montague_10_21_20_final/original.jpg 2x" alt="A silhouette of a person with blue spots" class="Image_root__J8Wlz" width="720" height="405"/></div><figcaption class="ArticleLeadArt_credit__xDQ7b"><span class="ArticleLeadArt_attribution__24Cg2">Julian Montague</span></figcaption></figure></div><div class="ArticleLayoutSection_sectionsContainer__16yMA"><section class="ArticleContent_root__3QHPz fonts-loaded"><figure class="left" data-apple-news-hide="1" style="max-width: 67.0px;"><picture style="display: block; position:relative; width:100%; height:0; overflow:hidden; padding-bottom:100.0%;"><img alt="" data-srcset="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/Xu_MgKLXTslj3JRQUMV-jU6WXq8=/672x672/media/img/posts/2020/06/Hamblin_Icon_final/original.jpg, https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/rFzx8COpOzaHiKMSI0TeLy_i6YI=/1344x1344/media/img/posts/2020/06/Hamblin_Icon_final/original.jpg 2x" class="lazyload" style="position:absolute; width:100%; height:100%; top:0; left:0; border:0;"></picture></figure><p><img alt="" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAPABAP///wAAACH5BAEKAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw==" title="Click and drag to move" width="15" height="15"><em>Editor’s Note: Every Wednesday, James Hamblin takes questions from readers about health-related curiosities, concerns, and obsessions. Have one? Email him at <a href="mailto:paging.dr.hamblin@theatlantic.com" data-omni-click="r'article',r'',d,r'intext',r'0',r'None'">paging.dr.hamblin@theatlantic.com</a>.</em></p><div data-template="hippo/components/ads/article-mobile.html" data-native="standard,gift" data-pos="boxinjector-m" class=" ad-boxinjector-m-wrapper"><gpt-ad targeting-pos="boxinjector-m1" targeting-native="standard,gift" class="c-ad c-ad--article-width s-native s-native--standard s-native--small kvr-native--article-mobile-flex" format="injector" lazy-load="2"><gpt-sizeset viewport-size="[0, 0]" sizes="mobile-wide,teads,native"></gpt-sizeset><gpt-sizeset viewport-size="[976, 0]" sizes=""></gpt-sizeset></gpt-ad></div><hr class="c-section-divider"><p><strong>Dear Dr. Hamblin,</strong></p><p>I’m perfectly healthy. I’m 42 and I exercise routinely, eat a whole-food, plant-based diet, and have excellent biomarkers. If I get the flu, chances are it will be mild and run its course. So why risk any potential negative side effects of a vaccine? To protect me against something that I might still get even with the shot? Even though I’m sure the risk is low, why should I potentially jeopardize my health? I guess I see only downsides and no upside.</p><div data-template="hippo/components/ads/article-house-desktop.html" data-pos="housepromo-d" id="housepromo-d" class=" ad-housepromo-d-wrapper"><gpt-ad targeting-pos="housepromo-d1" class="c-ad c-ad--house" format="promo" lazy-load="2"><gpt-sizeset viewport-size="[0, 0]" sizes=""></gpt-sizeset><gpt-sizeset viewport-size="[976, 0]" sizes="house"></gpt-sizeset></gpt-ad></div><p><strong>Todd Kelly</strong></p><p><em>Philadelphia, Pa.</em></p><hr class="c-section-divider"><p>Your concerns are widely shared, and your question is important. The answer is especially worth considering because the same logic that guides your decision will apply to the coronavirus vaccines in coming years.</p><p dir="ltr">Let’s start with the downsides. Any moral decision starts with accurately assessing the risk of taking an action. In this case, it’s as close to zero as anything modern medicine has to offer. If I were going to focus on risks, I’d be more worried about you getting hit by a car on your way to the pharmacy or doctor’s office than anything that might happen because of the shot.</p></section><section class="ArticleRecirc_inline__QG2Tj"><h2 class="ArticleRecirc_heading__c8Axp">Recommended Reading</h2><ul class="ArticleRecirc_list__37ci9"><li><div class="ArticleRecirc_itemRoot__1Jcqk"><figure class="ArticleRecirc_itemPhoto__qX9id"><a class="ArticleRecirc_itemLink__QSis8" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2020/10/paging-dr-hamblin-instruments-spread-coronavirus/616708/" title="Read More: Paging Dr. Hamblin: How Dangerous Are Woodwinds?" data-action="click link - recommended reading - image 1" data-label="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2020/10/paging-dr-hamblin-instruments-spread-coronavirus/616708/"><picture class="ArticleRecirc_itemMedia__1HN7t"><img class="ArticleRecirc_itemImage__361c-" alt="An illustration of woodwind instruments." src="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/kVaWst1sGQfHiJV4l4EYcm0WS-Q=/0x87:1319x1406/80x80/https://cdn.theatlantic.com/assets/media/img/mt/2020/10/Montague_10_14_20_final/original.jpg" srcSet="https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/kVaWst1sGQfHiJV4l4EYcm0WS-Q=/0x87:1319x1406/80x80/https://cdn.theatlantic.com/assets/media/img/mt/2020/10/Montague_10_14_20_final/original.jpg, https://cdn.theatlantic.com/thumbor/Mg9ob4B-xLrX09XavLRo8AY9iJU=/0x87:1319x1406/160x160/https://cdn.theatlantic.com/assets/media/img/mt/2020/10/Montague_10_14_20_final/original.jpg 2x"/></picture></a></figure><div class="ArticleRecirc_itemContent__jCvRY"><h3 class="ArticleRecirc_itemTitle__1DFk5"><a class="ArticleRecirc_itemLink__QSis8" href="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2020/10/paging-dr-hamblin-instruments-spread-coronavirus/616708/" data-action="click link - recommended reading - title 1" data-label="https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2020/10/paging-dr-hamblin-instruments-spread-coronavirus/